<h2>NEW TACTIC</h2>
<p>
  use nested divs and overflow:hidden to make triangles
  that can be styled like divs!
</p>

<div class="outer outer__1">
  <div class="inner inner__1"></div>
</div>

<p>now let's get that slide-in working</p>

<div class="outer outer__2">
  <div class="inner inner__2">
  </div>
</div>

<p>great! now get the background correct:</p>

<div class="outer outer__2">
  <div class="inner inner__3">
    <div class="slider"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<p>okay, but what about changing the shape of the triangle?</p>
<p>using hard sizes for inner means changing them every time you need a different shape</p>
<p>can it be done with percentages?</p>

<div class="outer outer__3">
  <div class="inner inner-pct__1">
    <div class="slider"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<p>cool. so what happens when you change the outer div in an attempt to edit the inner?</p>
<p>let's just maintain outer's aspect ratio for now.</p>

<div class="outer outer__4">
  <div class="inner inner-pct__1">
    <div class="slider"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<p>looks like you can scale this triangle!</p>
<p>how about a different aspect ratio?</p>
<div class="outer outer__5">
